  "response_text": "Gravity is a fundamental force of nature that causes any two masses to be attracted to each other. It is one of the four known forces in the universe, alongside electromagnetism, the strong nuclear force, and the weak nuclear force.\n\nThe concept of gravity can be explained through several key points:\n\n1. **Universal Gravitation**: Sir Isaac Newton formulated the law of universal gravitation in the 17th century. According to this law, every particle of matter in the universe attracts every other particle with a force that is directly proportional to the product of their masses and inversely proportional to the square of the distance between their centers. This means that the gravitational force between two objects increases as their masses increase and decreases as the distance between them increases.\n\n2. **Gravitational Field**: The gravitational field around an object is a region where another object experiences a force due to the first object's mass. The strength of the gravitational field at any point is equal to the gravitational force per unit mass",
